  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up as an immigrant in Los Angeles, I was always aware of how my background might affect my perception of what I could achieve. My parents had different educational paths—one with a PhD, the other with a vocational diploma—which taught me early that success isn't always tied to the same kind of schooling. When I started working in retail, I often thought about how my peers in STEM fields might feel when they're reminded of stereotypes about their group. For example, I've heard stories from coworkers who are women or people of color about how they feel pressured to prove themselves in math or science classes because of what others expect. That's stereotype threat: the anxiety that comes from being reminded of negative stereotypes about your group, which can actually hurt your performance. I believe we absolutely should address it. In my own experience, when I was younger, I'd avoid math problems because I thought I wasn't good at them, even though I could solve them. Now, as a dad to a young child and someone who spends time on social media, I've learned that small changes in how we talk about STEM can make a big difference. Instead of saying 'you're not good at this,' we should say 'let's try this together.' It's about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to learn without fear of judgment. The key is to acknowledge the problem and then build community, not just focus on fixing individual cases. For instance, my local community center has started workshops where people of all backgrounds can explore STEM through hands-on projects, and it's already helping to break down some of those barriers. So yes, we need to address stereotype threat in STEM—it's real, it affects real people, and it's something we can fix by being intentional about how we support each other.",
